description:
I finally got projectM to work with the Linux binary of VLC. I had some Milkdrop visualizers lying around that I could import into projectM and use as audio visualizers in VLC media player.

This video plays some demoscene music in addition to showing off the visualizers working in VLC media player.
fulltitle: Milkdrop in VLC Media Player using ProjectM in Pop!_OS (Linux)

comments.text:
@markusTegelanePlus I think I finally found the how-to, and I hope this serves as a reference for people who stumbled upon this video. It involved a RPM instead of a DEB, but still it worked. I googled "vlc-plugin-projectm " and several sites offering various RPM downloads popped up. I then downloaded one that said something about x86_64, extracted it, and found a file called "libprojectm_plugin . so". Then, under root privileges, I copied that to /usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/vlc/plugins/visualization. And voila, it worked! (I did all of this on Linux Mint 20.2 Cinnamon, by the way). Then I opened VLC, then an audio file, and in the top menu, under Audio > Visualizations, projectM appeared. It is possible to configure it under Tools > Preferences, by selecting "All" at the bottom and then going under Audio > Visualizations > projectM. Thanks for the idea though; it gave me a road map for attemting it.

Greetings from Colombia.
comments.author: @Alejandrium

comments.text:
I should add that depending on the distro, you may have VLC crash whenever you switch to projectM visualization while playing music. If that's the case, go and set the correct location for fonts at Tools > Preferences > All > Audio > Visualizations > projectM. If you don't know where DejaVu fonts are, just run this command in the terminal: find /usr/share/fonts | grep "DejaVu"
This should list all of the DejaVu fonts on your system if they are installed.
